Data dictionary¶

  • Ticker Symbol: an abbreviation used to uniquely identify the actions that are quoted in the stock market of a particular action in a particular stock market- Company: company name- GICS SECTOR: The specific economic sector assigned to a company by the standard for classification of the global industry (GICS) that best defines its commercial operations- Gics Sub Industry: The specific subindustria group assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its commercial operations- Current Price: current price of action in dollars- Price Change: percentage change in the price of shares in 13 weeks- Volatility: Standard deviation of the price of shares in the last 13 weeks- ROE: A measure of financial yield that is calculated by dividing net income from the equity of the shareholders (the equity of the shareholders is equal to the assets of a company except its debt)- Cash Ratio: The relationship between the total cash and equivalent reserves of a company and its total current liabilities.- Net Cash Flow: The difference between the tickets and outputs of a company of a company (in dollars)- Net Inome: Income less expenses, interest and taxes (in dollars)- Earnings Per Share: The net profit of the company divided by the number of ordinary shares it has in circulation (in dollars)- Estimated Shares Outstanding: Company Actions currently held by all its shareholders- P/E Ratio: Relationship between the current price of the company's shares and profits per share- P/B Ratio: Relationship between the price of the shares of the company per share and its book value per share (the book value of a company is the net difference between the total assets and the total liabilities of that company)

# We create the following function to draw a cash diagram and a histogram along the same scale.

def histogram_boxplot(df, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Número de filas de la cuadrícula de la subparcela = 2
        sharex=True,  # el eje x se compartirá entre todas las subparcelas
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )   # creando las 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=df, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )   # se creará un diagrama de caja y un triángulo indicará el valor medio de la columna
    sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # para histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Añadiendo la media al histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Añadiendo la mediana al histogram

# Function to create barloot diagrams
def labeled_barplot(df, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(df[feature])   # longitud de la columna
    count = df[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=df,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=df[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )   # porcentaje de cada clase de la categoría
        else:
            label = p.get_height()   # recuento de cada nivel de la categoría

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2    # ancho del plot
        y = p.get_height()  # largo del plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # anotar el porcentaje

    plt.show()  # se muestra el plot

# The following code line indicates the number of expected clusters (14)clusters = range(1, 15)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction = model.predict(k_means_df)
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(k_means_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / k_means_df.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Numero de Clusteres:", k, "\t Distorsión promedio:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")

Hierarchical grouping¶

Calculation of the Cofenetic correlation¶

In [66]:
# We create an HC_DF variable to save the value of the climbing subsethc_df = subset_scaled_df.copy()
In [ ]:
# List of distance metricsdistance_metrics =  ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]
# Link method listlinkage_methods =  ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]
## We add links
high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(hc_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
        print(
            "La correlación cofenética para {} distancia y {} vinculación es {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm
            
# Printing the combination of distance metric and liaison method with the highest cofenetic correlationprint('*'*100)
print(
    "La correlación cofenética más alta es {}, que se obtiene con {} distancia y {} vinculación.".format(
        high_cophenet_corr, high_dm_lm[0].capitalize(), high_dm_lm[1]
    )
)

Let's explore different linking methods only with the Euclidian distance.

In [68]:
# Link method listlinkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]
## We add links
high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for lm in linkage_methods:
    Z = linkage(hc_df, metric="euclidean", method=lm)
    c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
    print("La correlación cofenética para el enlace {} es {}.".format(lm, c))
    if high_cophenet_corr < c:
        high_cophenet_corr = c
        high_dm_lm[0] = "euclidean"
        high_dm_lm[1] = lm
        
# Printing the combination of distance metric and liaison method with the highest cofenetic correlationprint('*'*100)
print(
    "La correlación cofenética más alta es {}, que se obtiene con el enlace {}.".format(
        high_cophenet_corr, high_dm_lm[1]
    )
)

La correlación cofenética más alta es 0.9422540609560814, que se obtiene con el enlace average.

DENDAGRAMS CHECK¶

In [69]:
# Link method listlinkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# Read on to save the results of the calculation of the coferatic correlationcompare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]
compare = []

# To create an image of Sublootfig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will list through the list of previous linking methods# For each link method, we will draw the dendrogram and calculate the cofenetic correlationfor i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(hc_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

K-Means vs Hierarchical Grouping¶

  • Definitely the group K-Means last less to execute and with better interpretability than the hierarchical andthe check of dendograms, for the end user.Since the dendograms are not very legible to be interpreted.
  • The hierarchical group gave more different groups since it has different correlations than the K-Meansand obviously they are different groups.
  • There are several observations in the conglomerates or clusters of both groupings and it was in:In Cluster 4, with the same values ​​in both groupings and were these:1274.949951 3.190527 1.268340 29.000000 184.000000 -1671386000.000000 2551360000.000000 50.090000 50935516.070000 25.453183 -1.05242
  • 11 clusters were obtained as appropriate number for both groupings.

Practical information¶

  • Cluster 0 : It has greater number of companies, in the K-Mean group but the variables are not recommended to take this cluster into account. Companies that seek to enter the stock market with this cluster can realize that it is not just to enter their actions and already, but there are many variables at stake for their profitability.

  • Cluster 4 : In both groups the same values ​​came out in all variables. The companies under this cluster are chance since, the Net Inome is high, they would only have to pay attention to their cash flow.

  • Cluster 5 : It seems to be the perfect cluster to select in the hierarchical grouping, since all its variables are in positive numbers with a good net income. This group must concentrate more on the roe incorporation of better to improve the results after taxes.

  • Cluster 8 : In the K-Means grouping it was the best cluster. To decide which is the best cluster that grouping you have to have the experience in the field, in this case in the Stock Exchange;Ask ourselves what we want, good profitability, excellent profits before and after taxes in addition to having control over the shares of companies?, or that all this in positive numbers so that in the long term it is more productive?

  • Clusters in general : Speaking of Gics Sub Industry, which are the Sub Industries within the different sectors. It is clear that energy is one of the companies with more volatibility and lower rentable for investment.

Recommendations¶

  • Make an investment plan and find profitability goals, to know how much you can invest in the stock market and in what time.- A good starting point to invest in shares is to choose a debt instrument investment fund: reviewing the historical yields of this type of funds in the market.- Designing heritage administration, you can decide which percentage of the total will be invested in the stock market.It can range between 10% and 15%, depending on each company and its liquidity.- To start it is recommended to choose a debt instrument investment fund, reviewing the historical yields of this type of funds in the stock market.- It is always good to review periodically, along with an advisor, how your investments go.If they have not given the results that were expected to evaluate the necessary changes to forward the way.- Invest only with financial intermediaries that are properly authorized, regulated and supervised by the National Banking and Securities Commission.- Always consider investment in shares as a long -term investment.- Take care of the investment period.The share market is volatile, sometimes in the short term there are losses, so it is recommended to have an experienced advisor to see if it is necessary to endure and not sell.Probably at the end of the investment, it recovers.
